voice_to_text: My crush handed me a folded paper in the hallway titled 10 reasons I can't date you. Sophia handed me the folded paper and stood there watching. Open it. My hands shook as I unfolded it. 10 reasons I can't date you was written at the top. I looked up at her. She was biting her lip, looking nervous. Just read it, please. Reason No. 1, you're too funny. I can't focus in class when you're around Sophia. What is this breeding? Reason No. 2, you smell too good. It's honestly distracting. My face was burning. Was she seriously doing this in front of me, listing reasons I wasn't good enough? I don't understand. You will keep going, but I couldn't keep going. My eyes were blurring and I felt humiliated. Is this a joke? She looked confused. No. Why would this be a joke? Because you're literally listing reasons you can't date me, like I'm not good enough. Her face changed. Wait, you think these are actual reasons? What else would they be? The bell rang. Students pushed past us in the hallway. Sophia grabbed my arm. We need to talk after school, please. She walked away before I could respond, leaving me holding the list. I couldn't focus for the rest of the day. Every class, I kept pulling out the list and reading it. You're too nice to my friends. You have better style than me. You're too good at guitar. How are any of These real reasons not to date someone. I saw Sophia three times between classes. Each time she tried to catch my eye. Each time I looked away. At lunch, she sat with her friends and I watched her show them something on her phone. They all looked over at me and started laughing. My chest tightened. She was telling them about the list, about how she rejected me in the dumbest way possible. Luke sat down next to me. So what did she say? She wants to talk after school. Are you going to? I don't know. Maybe I should just let it go, bro. You need closure. In English class, our teacher paired us for a group project. Sophia moved her desk next to mine. Hey, she said softly. I didn't look at her, just pulled out my notebook. Are you mad at me? I'm not mad. You seem mad. I'm just confused why you'd write that list and then act like I'm the one who misunderstood. She was quiet for a moment. Can we please just talk after school? I promise it'll make sense. But nothing about this made sense. After class, I saw her in the hallway talking to Craig, the guy every girl liked. She was smiling, laughing at something he said. She looked relieved, like he was glad to be talking to someone who wasn't me. I almost didn't go. Stood by my locker for 10 minutes debating, but something made me walk toward the Bleachers anyway. Sophia was sitting on the bottom row, knees pulled to her chest.

Dad never smiled or talked to them like they were his children. He gave orders like they were soldiers. Sit up straight, chew slower. Don't touch your face. The kids followed every command instantly. No normal kid is that obedient. When I brought their check, I heard the dad say, if you embarrass me again like last time, you know what happens when we get home. The kids nodded quickly, looking terrified. My stomach dropped. I heard that tone before from my own stepdad when I was little. I went to the kitchen and told Janet what I was seeing. She came out to refill their water and observe the table for a few minutes. When she came back, her face was pale. She said we needed to call someone, but she wasn't sure who. The dad paid in cash and started gathering the kids to leave. The ten year old was limping slightly as they walked toward the door. That's when I noticed she had a bruise on her arm that hadn't been there when they sat down. Actually, it had been there. I just hadn't seen it under her long sleeves until she reached for some. Janet made the call while I watched them through the window. The dad was gripping both kids shoulders really tight as they walked to his car. The kids moved like robots. No talking, no normal kid behaviour, just following orders. The police arrived 15 minutes later. They caught up with the car. Two blocks away. Turns out the dad wasn't even their real father. He'd taken them from their mom's house during what was supposed to be a supervised visit. The kids hadn't eaten a real meal in two days. The mom showed up at the restaurant later that night, crying and thanking us over and over. She said the kids had been trained to act perfect in public so no one would ask questions. The dad had threatened them with worse punishments if anyone found out.

voice_to_text: Late into the night, a man lay with his wife while her younger sister secretly watched from the next room. Burning with frustration, the girl tried to distract herself with nothing but a glowing light bulb. Then came the storm. A raging typhoon tore through Lynn's home, leaving her with nowhere to run. With her little daughter in her arm, she set off to find her husband working far away in another city. Penniless and Desperate, Lynn slipped onto a passenger ship without a ticket. After disembarking, she stumbled upon a lost wallet, and instead of keeping it, she returned it to its owner. Grateful stranger handed her some cash to help her on her way. To avoid unwanted attention, Lynn chose a seat at the back of a long distance bus. But while nursing her baby, she caught the eyes of two thugs. Just as they approached, a man with a gun stepped in, stopping them cold, and even paid her fare. Feeling a rare sense of safety, Lynn began to share her story. When she was only five, her father died in a car. Her mother lost her sanity soon after, and then her life. Lynn and her brother were left on their own. To survive, their aunt sold her brother for a handful of money. Eleven years later, Lynn had grown into a young woman, only to fall prey to her uncle's dark intention eventually.
